                <head>74. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On August 27, 1974, President’s Counselor for Economic Policy <persName
                        corresp="#p_RK1">Kenneth Rush</persName> sent President <persName
                        corresp="#p_FGR1">Gerald Ford</persName> a memorandum on the U.S. position
                    on gold. Attached to the memorandum were three documents: Economic Decision
                    Memorandum #2, referred to in <ref target="#d69">Document 69</ref>; <persName
                        corresp="#p_RK1">Rush</persName>’s June 4 memorandum “transmitting a
                    suggested U.S. position on gold prepared by Secretary <persName
                        corresp="#p_SWE1">Simon</persName>,” <ref target="#d68">Document 68</ref>;
                    and Council of Economic Advisers Chairman <persName corresp="#p_SH3">Herbert
                        Stein</persName>’s June 3 memorandum on gold, <ref target="#d67">Document
                        67</ref>. A notation on <persName corresp="#p_RK1">Rush</persName>’s August
                    27 memorandum to President <persName corresp="#p_FGR1">Ford</persName> indicates
                    the President saw it.</p>
                <p>On September 25, President’s Special Assistant <persName corresp="#p_JJ2">Jerry
                        Jones</persName> wrote to <persName corresp="#p_RK1">Rush</persName>
                    concerning the U.S. position on gold: “Your memorandum to the President of
                    August 27 on the above subject has been reviewed and the following comments were
                    made on September 24: —I am returning this to you as I clean up desk. Several
                    weeks ago we had meeting on this. What was decision? Or, was position deferred?
                    Please follow-up with the appropriate action.” (<persName corresp="#p_FGR1"
                        >Ford</persName> Library, President’s Handwriting File, Subject File, Box
                    19, Finance—Gold)</p>
            </div>
